What Are Web Vitals?
Web Vitals is a set of standardised, user-centric performance metrics defined by Google that quantify the real-world experience of a webpage's loading speed, interactivity, and visual stability, directly influencing both user satisfaction and search engine rankings.
ℹ️ ️Core Web Vitals (CWV) — the three metrics that affect Google Search ranking: LCP (Largest Contentful Paint), INP (Interaction to Next Paint), and CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift). These are measured on real users via Chrome User Experience Report (CrUX).
Every Metric Explained
Each vital measures a different dimension of the user experience. Here’s a complete breakdown of all 8 metrics — their definition, how the browser calculates them, and what “good” looks like.

• LCP (Largest Contentful Paint): Time until the largest image or text block in the viewport is fully rendered. Measures perceived load speed.
Good ≤ 2.5s
NI ≤ 4s
Poor > 4s

• INP (Interaction to Next Paint): Latency of the slowest interaction (click, tap, key) from first input to next frame painted and replaced FID in 2024.
Good ≤ 200ms
NI ≤ 500ms
Poor > 500ms

• CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift): Sum of all unexpected layout shift scores. Each shift = impact fraction × distance fraction. Measures visual stability.
Good ≤ 0.1
NI ≤ 0.25s
Poor > 0.25

• TTFB (Time to First Byte): Time from navigation start until the first byte of the HTTP response is received by the browser. Diagnoses server and network speed.
Good ≤ 800ms
NI ≤ 1.8s
Poor > 1.8s

• FCP (First Contentful Paint): Time until the browser renders any content — text, image, SVG, or canvas. First signal that the page is actually loading.
Good ≤ 1.8s
NI ≤ 3s
Poor > 3s

• TBT (Total Blocking Time): Sum of all blocking portions of long tasks (>50ms) between FCP and TTI. Each task’s blocking time = duration − 50ms.
Good ≤ 200ms
NI ≤ 600ms
Poor > 600ms

• FID (First Input Delay (deprecated)): Delay before the browser could process the user’s first interaction. Replaced by INP in March 2024. Still measured in some tools.
Good ≤ 100ms
NI ≤ 300ms
Poor > 300ms

• SI (Speed Index): How quickly content is visually populated during page load. Calculated from video frame analysis. Lower = more content visible sooner.
Good ≤ 3.4s
NI ≤ 5.8s
Poor > 5.8s
How the Browser Calculates Each Metric
LCP uses PerformanceObserver with largest-contentful-paint entries. The browser continuously tracks the largest image, video poster, or block of text in the viewport and records a new entry each time a larger element is painted. The final LCP value is reported when the user interacts or the tab becomes hidden.
INP was introduced to capture the full distribution of interaction latency, not just the first one (FID’s flaw). It measures every click, tap, and key event from input to next paint — and reports the worst one (excluding outliers above the 98th percentile). This means one bad interaction tanks your INP score.
CLS calculates a layout shift score for each unexpected shift: impact_fraction × distance_fraction. Impact fraction is the percentage of the viewport affected by the shift. Distance fraction is how far the shifted element moved as a percentage of the viewport height. It uses session windows (max 5s, max 1s gap) and reports the worst window.
TTFB comes directly from the Navigation Timing API: responseStart − navigationStart. It includes DNS, TCP, TLS handshake, and server processing time — making it a key indicator of backend performance.
TBT is a lab metric (Lighthouse only). Any main-thread task longer than 50ms is a “long task.” TBT accumulates taskDuration − 50ms for each long task between FCP and Time to Interactive. It’s the closest lab proxy for INP.
